  "narrative_arc": "Young Black man confined to the Black Belt of 1930s Chicago by restrictive covenants. Wright documents the physical architecture of segregation — the rat-infested kitchenette apartment, the invisible boundaries of the ghetto, the white neighborhoods he can only enter as a servant. When he accidentally kills, the legal system treats him as the monster it always assumed he was.",
  "why_this_character_matters": "Bigger's dome is the foundational text of environmental determinism. Wright argues that every system — housing, legal, economic, community — conspired to create Bigger. Building his dome with real 1930s Chicago data proves or disproves Wright's thesis.",
